#. type: subsubsection{#2}
#: data/usage.tex:685
msgid "Ecryptfs"
msgstr ""

#. type: document
#: data/usage.tex:692
msgid ""
"On GNU/Linux Debian and Ubuntu, you can easily create a directory Private in "
"your home directory. This directory will be encrypted using the password you "
"use to connect when you start your computer. Just type ecryptfs-setup-"
"private in a terminal to create it. You have to logout/login agan. You can "
"then put the work directory of Paperwork in it."
msgstr ""

#. type: document
#: data/usage.tex:695
msgid ""
"Once the directory has been created, you can also store Paperwork index in "
"it:"
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: data/usage.tex:698
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ mv ~/.local/share/paperwork ~/Private/paperwork_index\n"
"$ ln -s ~/Private/paperwork_index ~/.local/share/paperwork"
msgstr ""

#. type: subsubsection{#2}
#: data/usage.tex:701
msgid "Encfs"
msgstr ""

#. type: document
#: data/usage.tex:704
msgid ""
"Encfs can also be used to create encrypted directories easily. However, "
"beware that Encfs seems to have some security weaknesses."
msgstr ""

#. type: verbatim
#: data/usage.tex:706
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ encfs ~/.papers ~/papers"
msgstr ""

